<TEXT>
a demolition worker was buried under several 
tons of rubble when seven stories of a parking garage partially 
collapsed in the downtown area 
authorities identified the trapped worker as basilio barrios 
36 and said rescue crews prepared to use an 80ton crane to dig 
him from 10 to 20 feet of rubble 
two other workers escaped on their own and a third was freed a 
short time later by district of columbia firemen authorities said 
battalion chief bill embrey of the dc fire department said 
we will stay here as long as it takes to get him out 
fire officials worked carefully to rescue barrios but estimated 
the operation will take time because the building is unstable and 
could collapse more investigators are looking into the matter 
authorities said the workers were performing routine demolition 
work on the second floor of the parking garage two stories had 
been previously removed from the ninestory structure 
barrios was believed to be cutting through a length of steel on 
the second floor of the garage when several stories of concrete 
began crashing down authorities said there is little hope that he 
survived 
after the building collapse workers brought in a police dog to 
help search for barrios body the dog recovered the hose to the 
torch barrios had been holding officials said 
a relative at the scene said barrios came to the united states 
about a year ago from guatemala to make money for his wife and five 
children he left behind barrios had planned to return to guatemala 
in june the relative said 
</TEXT>
