<TEXT>
us courts need more judges particularly in 
border regions burdened with a heavy load of drug cases says chief 
justice william h rehnquist 
from the federal law enforcement perspective the war on drugs 
will fail if the judiciary is not given the judgeships necessary to 
do the job the supreme court chief said sunday in his annual 
yearend report on the federal court system 
some courts especially in border states are approaching the 
outer limits of caseload and fatigue from handling drugrelated 
cases he said noting that one in four criminal cases handled by 
the federal courts is drugrelated 
rehnquist urged congress to take immediate action to create 
the 59 additional trial judgeships and 16 more appellate judgeships 
requested last october by the us judicial conference the 
policymaking arm of the federal court system rehnquist heads the 
conference 
to date congress has authorized 575 federal trial judgeships 
and 168 appellate judgeships no new judgeship has been created 
since 1984 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
a boston music educator a new york pianist 
and a los angeles trumpeteer received 20000 fellowships from the 
national endowment for the arts that also place them in the jazz 
hall of fame 
george russell cecil taylor and gerald wilson were awarded the 
jazz master fellowships sunday for exceptional artistic merit in 
the field of jazz the trio joins 25 other jazz luminaries 
including dizzie gillespie count basie and ella fitzgerald who 
have been selected by the independent federal agency since the 
awards began in 1982 
russell 66 of boston is a composer arranger jazz theorist 
drummer pianist and band leader who has been on the faculty of the 
new england conservatory since 1969 and is leader of the living 
time orchestra 
taylor 60 of new york city is a pianist and composer who was 
cited for his pioneering influences on modern jazz including a 
piano playing style that features use of open palms fists elbows 
and forearms 
wilson 71 of los angeles is a mississippiborn composer 
arranger band leader and trumpeter who once worked as a sideman 
and arranger for count basie and duke ellington and has led 
several successful big bands of his own starting in the 1940s 
</TEXT>
