<TEXT>
the death toll among police officers killed in 
the line of duty fell to 97 in 1989 down from 167 in 1988 says 
the national association of chiefs of police 
fifty officers died of gunshot wounds 32 in traffic accidents 
eight in plane crashes and seven others in stabbings fights or 
other incidents on duty the group said sunday 
increased use of bullet resistant jackets and the upgraded 
training in law enforcement agencies we believe has played a role 
in reversing a trend that we thought would never end regarding the 
deaths of law enforcement officers david waud the associations 
chief of staff services said in a statement 
the average age of officers killed was 27 in 1989 the most 
dangerous day on average was thursday and the most dangerous 
hours between 10 pm and 2 am 
texas led the count with 11 officers killed followed by new 
york and florida each with eight and mississippi and california 
each with seven 
