<TEXT>
william scott a british artist acclaimed for his 
stilllife paintings and drawings of simple foods and kitchen 
utensils has died at age 76 at his home in southwest england 
scott who died thursday of alzheimers disease at his home 
outside bath played a leading role in bringing british painting 
back into the international mainstream after world war ii isolation 
he represented his country successfully at art festivals 
throughout the 1950s and 1960s in 1961 he won the international 
critics prize at the sao paulo biennale 
in 1966 he was named a commander of the british empire 
the son of an irish signwriter scott was born feb 15 1913 in 
greenock scotland and was brought up in northern ireland he 
studied at the belfast college of art and the royal academy of art 
in london in the late 1920s and 1930s 
scott initially reacted against the surrealist tendencies of the 
1930s but by the 1960s his work had become increasingly abstract 
he once described himself as belonging to the generation in 
between the representational and nonrepresentational phases of 
modern art 
he was noted above all for his paintings of objects such as 
kitchen pots and pans baskets and bottles eggs and loaves of 
bread laid out on kitchen tables 
his works are characterized by an exceptional ability to 
control the rhythmical spacing of shapes and the division of 
picture areas commented the times of london 
his often very beautiful colors ranged from the richly 
voluptuous to a fondness for pure black and white a blend of 
sensuality and austerity which is characteristic of his work 
few british painters have been more widely represented in the 
worlds galleries scotts work is included in permanent 
collections of the museum of modern art in new york the goteborg 
museum in sweden the national gallery of modern art in rome and 
the tate museum in london 
survivors include his wife mary lucas and two sons james and 
robert 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

