<TEXT>
the words of a south vietnamese soldier 
hold new meaning for david pye as he prepares to return to the 
country that still feeds his nightmares 
the young man who served on a night patrol with pye told him 
more than two decades ago i would like to be able to lay my head 
down at night and not hear small arms fire 
pye who runs a veterans outreach center in this seaside town 
north of boston is one of 12 veterans returning to vietnam this 
month to see if a peacetime visit will help silence the sounds of 
combat that echo in their dreams and memories 
the 16day excursion sponsored by a university of massachusetts 
center devoted to the examination of war and its aftermath is part 
of a study on posttraumatic stress disorder the flashbacks 
nightmares and depression that afflict many veterans who fought in 
vietnam a second group of veterans who also will participate in 
the study is scheduled to make a trip in may 
all the veterans participating in the trip are counselors 
there have been some ad hoc studies done but they are not 
conclusive said kevin bowen the joiner centers executive 
director and vietnam veteran there has been a lot of anecdotal 
evidence that going back to vietnam has a real healing effect on 
vets 
researchers will conduct interviews and tests on the 
participants before they go to vietnam immediately after they 
return and six months and a year after the trip 
by studying the responses over time the researchers will try to 
determine whether visiting vietnam reduced the level of post 
traumatic stress 
since learning he would be returning to vietnam pye said he has 
had several nightmares dreams he hasnt had for 18 years the 
closer we get to the date the higher my anxiety is he said 
pye 43 first came to vietnam on a troop ship on new years eve 
in 1966 he remembers watching the fireworks for a few days 
before landing i was of course scared he said 
gumersindo gomez another veteran who will be traveling with the 
group said his dreams often take him to a jungle river where he 
wades kneedeep in water while the enemy shoots from the sides 
every night ive been having nightmares gomez said these 
are combatrelated nightmares the fear of being killed 
neither gomez nor pye has returned to vietnam before and 
despite the anxiety both feel at the upcoming journey the two men 
hope the experience will help them exorcise old ghosts 
bowen remembers the anxiety of waiting to return to vietnam for 
the first time he was drafted into the army after dropping out of 
college and served from 196869 
bowen has been back four times he first went in 1987 with a 
group of college professors and since then on various projects 
sponsored by the joiner foundation 
in many ways the most profound observations were also the 
simplest the country was silent and the land was beautiful 
there was nothing in the sky bowen said 
now bowen has established a new relationship with vietnam and 
its people 
i got to places where i lost friends and that was very 
powerful he said going to the memorial in washington was one 
thing to be able to say goodbye to be able to do that there is 
just as important 
