<TEXT>
one of the latest superfund successes 
felt like a long wait to ralph bidgood whose fouryear ordeal 
began the night he discovered some people probing the dirt behind 
his mobile home 
there were people in white suits and rubber gloves and rubber 
boots walking around and i started wondering what was going on 
bidgood said 
he found that his home sat atop a toxic waste dump that had been 
oozing arsenic benzene cyanide and lead into drinking wells and 
the nearby black river and seavers brook for up to 40 years 
an epa official termed the site a chemical time bomb and 
said it was the only superfund site in new england that had people 
living on top of it 
bidgoods ordeal is over on friday his trailer like 33 
others in the park was purchased by the polluters and bidgood 
moved to an apartment three remaining trailers will soon be 
purchased 
this is the first and probably the only site in new england 
that involves permanent relocation of residents said paul 
keough acting regional administrator for the us environmental 
protection agency he termed the site a time bomb in 1988 well 
after it was added to the superfund list in 1982 
in an agreement announced last month four parties 
springfield emhart industries inc textron inc and 
browningferris industries have admitted liability for the 
pollution and agreed to pay the epa 175 million the site was 
once a town landfill 
they also will provide millions to build a pipeline system to 
collect the seepage and a treatment plant to remove the chemicals 
town manager william steele said the treatment and monitoring will 
continue for 30 years 
the companies also set up a trust fund to buy the mobile homes 
the total cleanup cost could reach 15 million keough said he 
said he could not estimate how much of that would be federal money 
nor could he say how much in federal funds has been spent so far 
the epa also has identified nine other parties that may be held 
liable for the pollution that investigation is continuing 
although the epa has been criticized by state and local 
officials for the long process most officials agree that a 
settlement probably would not have been reached without its 
involvement 
the potentially responsible parties would like to pretend that 
those dumps dont exist at all said former us sen robert 
stafford of vermont who drafted the superfund legislation while 
chairman of the committee on environment and public works they 
wont do anything until the epa gets after them 
the federal superfund program cleans toxic waste dumps around 
the country a 1985 reauthorization of the program set aside 85 
billion for the cleanups the epas national priorities list 
currently names about 1250 hazardous waste sites 
the epa tries to get polluters to pay for the cleanups 
nationally it has collected more than 1 billion in cleanup 
expenses 
springfield a town of about 10000 in southeastern vermont was 
dominated by its machine tools industry for about 150 years 
from 1946 to 1968 those factories dumped their industrial waste 
in the town landfill which was built on eight acres on a hill 
overlooking the town 
everything was done according to the environmental regulations 
at the time steele said the whole thing was done with the 
idea well lets do something environmentally sound rather than 
dump it in the river lets put it in this landfill 
after the dump reached capacity and closed it ultimately was 
used as a mobile home park beginning in 1971 about the same time 
that surrounding residents began complaining of odor and 
discoloration of their well water 
they studied the problem for eight years steele said 
there was a perception that the epa was taking too long 
keough said the lengthy process is necessary and added that the 
epas cautious and expensive pace may even encourage polluters to 
admit liability 
i think theres a feeling in the private sector that they can 
do it quicker and cheaper than the federal government keough 
said its to their advantage to get on board early 
bidgood 43 moved to the site several years after it was put on 
the superfund list but said he didnt know that until several years 
later when he saw the environmental inspectors digging in his yard 
bidgood settled with the polluters for 31000 while packing 
his belongings thursday he vowed not to release the polluters from 
any future liability if he gets ill 
im not really scared about it but im not signing off on 
it he said i just want to get out of here 
