the disease about how much a hospital should do to protect workers 
from aids 
the case is terribly important because it could set a 
precedent that hospitals are liable when an employee is infected 
said larry gostin associate professor of health law at the harvard 
school of public health and executive director of the american 
society of law and medicine 
even before the trial there has been sensationalism 
there have been charges that the defendants lawyers stalled so 
prego would die before the case went to trial the state attorney 
generals office subpoenaed her sympathy cards to ferret out 
sympathetic jurors 
in legal briefs lawyers for the health and hospitals corp 
which operates city hospitals have complained about newspapers 
sleazy reporting on the case charging that they printed 
propaganda without regard to the truth 
it comes down to what a jury will believe happened in january 
1983 
prego was a medical school graduate working under a licensed 
physician in preparation for a hospital internship she says she 
was cleaning up after an intern dr joyce fogel when she reached 
into a tangle of gauze and bed linens in which fogel had 
negligently and improperly left a bloody needle 
the hospitals side dr fogel has stated adamantly that she 
wasnt present when the blood was drawn and did not cause the 
injury she wasnt there said fred winters spokesman for 
health and hospitals 
there are two different versions of how dr prego received her 
injury said winters the defense has refused to elaborate 
wilner said prego reported her injury because the needle had 
been used to draw blood from a known aids patient 
the powers that be assured her there were no reports of a 
health care worker getting aids through occupational exposure at 
that time that may very well have been a true statement wilner 
said 
prego argues that the hospital failed to provide 
punctureresistant containers for contaminated needles winters 
said hhc hospitals were in the forefront of following the known 
precautions against aids transmission at the time 
in 1985 prego tested positive for exposure to the aids virus 
when she agreed to take part in a study on the incidence of the 
virus among healthcare workers 
prego says the researcher dr sheldon landesman of the state 
university of new york told hospital personnel she was infected 
even though she had been promised the results were confidential he 
has denied any breach of confidentiality but she has sued him as 
well 
in november 1987 prego was diagnosed as having aids she 
completed a fellowship from home and now works on research when her 
health permits 
despite her illness she intends to testify at trial she is not 
available for interviews 
the centers for disease control has documented 19 cases and are 
investigating several others of health workers who contracted the 
virus at work twelve of them were stuck by needles said cdc 
spokesman chuck fallis 
kings county hospital and the hhc say they acted prudently to 
protect employees from aids they argue that pregos should be a 
workers compensation case 
prego has said she fears the city wants me to die before 
trial can start 
hospital officials vehemently deny that 
we have taken every step we can to expedite dr pregos case 
so that she will have an opportunity to pursue her claim said 
winters he said the hospital had waived a procedure that would 
have delayed the trial another year 
</TEXT>
