<TEXT>
labor and industry officials today announced 
tentative settlement of the bitter ninemonth pittston coal strike 
that has idled 1700 miners in virginia west virginia and kentucky 
we came to what i really believe is a reasonable solution 
to both sides it is fair and it is honorable special mediator 
wj usery said at a news conference in the office of labor 
secretary elizabeth dole 
agreement was reached in the first hours of 1990 following six 
days of marathon negotiations 
united mine workers president richard trumka said it is too 
early to say when the miners will return to work and that they 
would first have to ratify the agreement 
terms of the settlement were not disclosed with both sides 
saying they wanted the miners to hear details from their leaders 
trumka said the specifics should be in the hands of the rank and 
file within eight to 10 days 
both sides they were happy with the agreement 
we just couldnt be happier to stand before you today we 
think weve met the essential objectives of all those concerned 
said pittston co chairman paul w douglas 
mrs dole said one of the most difficult issues was the 
longterm security of the pension and health care benefits for 
the miners and their families 
pittston had balked at continuing payments into a pension fund 
a move that had preciptated the walkout 
mrs dole said she will appoint a commission to review all 
aspects of the pension and healthcare issue and make 
recommendations to me for dealing with it 
she said the commission would report to her within six months 
trumka stressed the commission was not part of the settlement 
and said the provisions for resolving the dispute over pittston 
payments did not involve any type of interim arrangment 
the funds issue has been settle between pittston and the 
united mine workers the union president said 
the strike which was punctuated by large labor rallies 
vandalism and rockthrowing confrontations between strikers and 
other company workers began april 5 
organized labor rallied around the strike with some 46000 coal 
workers in 10 states walking off their jobs in sympathy strikes at 
one point 
in charleston west virginia gov gaston caperton said i 
think that its the greatest way we could start the new year this 
has been a very long strike and a very difficult strike for the 
miners and their families 
both sides had been under a gag order during the talks at a 
downtown washington hotel 
usery a former labor secretary had said he hoped to reach a 
tentative settlement by new years day 
the union workers struck in april after pittston decided to end 
contributions to the umw retirement and health plans for some 
130000 workers the union said the decision could cause other coal 
companies to follow suit and retired miners would lose their 
benefits 
pittston the nations largest coal exporter says it cannot 
afford the payments because it faces high costs to ship its coal 
overseas 
the umw also said job security was threatened because pittston 
had refused to go along with an industry agreement to give laidoff 
workers the first chance at new job openings 
the umw raised a strike fund of more than 100 million giving 
striking workers about 200 a week to live on plus a christmas 
bonus miners normally earn up to 635 a week the union also is 
facing fines of 635 million for violating court orders limiting 
picketing and other strike activities 
pittston hired replacement workers but production has been well 
below prestrike levels the company reported its coal operations 
lost 36 million in the second quarter of 1989 and 98 million in 
the third quarter compared with profits of 9 million and 74 
million in the respective quarters of 1988 
