<TEXT>
editors note gene kramer a member of the associated press 
staff in washington was the aps prague correspondent in 196872 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
week after week despairing czechoslovaks saw 
the tormented face of oncejaunty alexander dubcek on television 
imploring calm and discipline while he waged a losing struggle to 
salvage some freedoms of the 1968 prague spring 
that was in occupied czechoslovakia after soviet and warsaw pact 
troops invaded nearly 22 years ago dubcek faded from view in late 
1969 and was seldom mentioned publicly during a politically grim 
prague winter that lasted a generation 
czechoslovakias political winter is ending now with a dramatic 
sovietblessed peaceful rollback of hardline communist rule last 
thursday dubcek was elected chairman of the federal assembly 
restoring him to honor and position after two decades in political 
oblivion 
also dissident playwright vaclav havel was elected president of 
the republic czechoslovakias first noncommunist state chief 
since eduard benes resigned in 1948 
dubceks return to official life at age 68 is regarded as 
historic justice in a country that made him one of communisms few 
idolized party leaders there even were dubcek fan clubs after the 
soviet invasion 
but popular demands for multiparty democracy suggest 
czechoslovaks will not settle now for what dubcek offered 22 years 
ago socialism with a human face 
dubcek said in 1968 he wanted to transform czechoslovakias 
hardline stalinist system into a kinder gentler form of communist 
rule that permitted free assembly and speech he said the 
communists should preserve their monopoly of power not through 
repression but by earning the right to lead 
dubcek ousted from party leadership and later from membership 
has not said whether he will seek reinstatement 
a prominent czechoslovakamerican ohio state university 
historian and journalism professor jiri hochman said the communist 
party has become irrelevant and dubcek must know it but he 
said knowing him i would guess he would like to get back in 
the party 
prague spring euphoria in czechoslovakia was marked by a 
series of cliffhanging facedowns between the dubcek camp and 
forces headed by soviet leader leonid brezhnev dubcek argued that 
reforms would rejuvenate rather than weaken communism 
even after the soviet invasion popular outrage in 
czechoslovakia enabled the dubcekites to hang on for months of 
struggle to preserve some freedoms 
support for dubcek upset soviet plans to install a puppet 
government and prompted the kremlin to bring dubcek prime minister 
oldrich cernik and other arrested prague leaders to moscow to 
negotiate their resumption of office and a forced program of 
normalization 
with a new slogan of we are with you be with us the 
haggard sadfaced dubcek made frequent television appearances 
cautioning his countrymen not to provoke the soviets 
he often broke the bad news about normalization measures 
that included ouster of popular leaders temporary basing of 
soviet troops in czechoslovakia and restored censorship 
some critics say today that dubcek gave in too easily failing 
to exploit his own popularity and the countrys solidarity 
dubcek never once drew a line on the rollback and warned the 
soviets not to cross it said dr jiri kotas a czech who has lived 
in exile in canada since 1979 and is organizing a conservative 
party to enter czechoslovakias promised free elections in june 
the kremlin slowly achieved the results brezhnev sought some 
said the prague spring really ended with the ice hockey riots 
in march 1969 
czechoslovakias victory over the soviet union in a semifinal 
match at the stockholm world championships unleashed pentup 
czechoslovak political feelings dancing in the snowcovered 
streets turned into antisoviet rioting 
moscow branded the episode a serious provocation and threatened 
to redeploy military force against civilians dubcek went on 
television with an urgent request for peace and discipline 
on april 17 1969 hardliner gustav husak replaced him as party 
chief and dubcek was demoted to federal assembly chairman 
ironically the same post he reassumed thursday 
in december 1969 dubcek was sent as ambassador to turkey 
passing up an opportunity to defect to the west he returned to 
czechoslovakia and in mid1970 was expelled from the communist 
party 
dubcek spent the ensuing years clerking and running a forestry 
office in slovakia 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP900101-0063 </DOCNO>
