<TEXT>
president vaclav havel who spent 
more than five years in jail for his political beliefs on monday 
declared a broad new years amnesty and reduced sentences for 
prison inmates 
it was not immediately clear how many prisoners would be freed 
under the amnesty or how many would benefit from sentence 
reductions 
havel declared the amnesty three days after he was elected 
president capping a peaceful revolution that ended 41 years of 
communist rule in this country 
the new years day decree applies to all prisoners with the 
exception of those indicted for abuse of authority of public 
official the official ctk news agency said 
that charge has already been levied against former prague 
communist party boss miroslav stepan considered responsible for 
violent police handling of a peaceful student demonstration on nov 
17 stepan was detained dec 23 and faces up to 10 years in prison 
if convicted 
stepan and excommunist party chief milos jakes have been 
expelled from the party for serious political mistakes but 
jakes so far has not been charged 
havel in his new years address said he was declaring the 
amnesty and reduction of sentences for humanitarian reasons 
there are many prisoners in our country who must live in 
jails that do not awaken the better part of what is in every 
human being and which humiliate people destroy them physically 
and spiritually havel said in the nationally televised address 
hours before the amnesty was declared 
at the same time i appeal to the prisoners to understand that 
40 years of improper investigations trials and jailing cannot be 
eliminated overnight he said 
inmates of at least 18 prisons staged hunger strikes last month 
protesting inadequate conditions 
havel himself spent more than five years in jail for his 
political convictions and is a known critic of the czechoslovak 
judicial system 
his decree reduces sentences for intentional acts by one third 
and sentences for criminal acts out of negligence by one half 
before he stepped down dec 10 former president gustav husak 
freed all those who opposition leaders considered political 
prisoners 
however opposition sources say at least six people are in jail 
on charges of espionage sentenced in secret trials on dubious 
evidence 
such sentences will be reexamined by the prosecutor general 
according to the text of the amnesty 
cases of terrorism murder rape and sexual abuse are excluded 
from the amnesty but all of these sentences are reduced by one 
year 
the amnesty wipes out all misdemeanor charges as well as 
suspended sentences including financial fines unless they stem from 
a criminal act 
havel asked the prosecutor general to reexamine sentences 
handed down to pregnant women mothers of children under 15 years 
of age old and handicapped people 
in a separate statement havel appointed pavol sitar the new 
prosecutor general 
</TEXT>
