<TEXT>
howard fogelman was shot seven times in vietnam 
losing all of his teeth and much of his confidence 
he now lives in the nations first homeless shelter for 
veterans sunday fogelman and 13 fellow residents felt the 
memories flooding back as they watched born on the fourth of 
july a new film about a wounded veterans struggle to cope 
the vets praised the oliver stone movie as they emerged from a 
showing of the film saying they identified with its portrayal of 
the isolation felt by veterans returning from the war 
but unlike reallife vet ron kovic played by tom cruise who 
leads antiwar demonstrators and finally feels at home by 1975 
fogelman and his colleagues are still waging their own war for 
dignity in america 
they feel they are losing 
at their shelter the veterans have curfews and other rules they 
say are better suited for children than former us servicemen 
some of whom have emotional wounds even though bullet wounds have 
mostly healed 
fogelman has a large dent in his face where a bullet entered 
and no teeth as a result of the shooting his last set of false 
teeth wore out two years ago and he says bureaucratic red tape has 
blocked him from replacing them 
without teeth he has remained jobless and homeless it has a 
lot to do with your confidence he said you dont want to 
talk 
drugs prescribed during his recovery from the facial wound he 
said led to a drug habit at home hes now in a methadone program 
and he suffers from posttraumatic stress which for him means 
you could just be sitting and you see images coming on the bus or 
the train 
he returned home in 1967 he said to a completely different 
country 
it seemed they were protesting everything especially the war 
it was pretty bad coming home im not bitter now in this country 
youve got to do for yourself fogelman said 
norman siegel executive director of the new york civil 
liberties union said he felt angry after watching the movie and 
hearing kovic say he felt he was home again 
i dont think these guys feel theyre back home yet they 
still have not reconnected he said 
its an outrage that theres not enough services and resources 
for the homeless veterans siegel said that ending is 1976 and 
its now 14 years later were beginning the 90s and youve got 
hundreds of thousands of people who are homeless and hundreds of 
homeless vets perhaps thousands and its not only in new york city 
but in cities across the country 
the group included two vets ben colon 36 and earl beddoe 41 
who have been on a liquid diet since dec 17 as a form of protest 
for better conditions at their shelter run by the salvation army in 
queens 
i believe we gave the best years of our lives veterans should 
never be homeless said colon who walks with a cane because of a 
war injury we need congress to remember our wounds are not 
healed yet 
the veterans are asking for a say in how the shelter where 400 
veterans stay is operated they say they are treated without 
compassion by the staff and note that only two of 80 on salary are 
homeless veterans they are asking for job training and homes 
its the quest for dignity said veteran kevin brown 29 
not that the country owes us anything but the country shouldnt 
forget thats all 
