sudans military leader called on 
southern rebels monday to agree to a third round of peace talks 
toward ending almost seven years of civil war 
adressing a rally marking the 34th anniversary of sudans 
independence attended by an estimated 150000 people lt gen omar 
hassan elbashir said he hopes 1990 will be a year of peace 
i call anew on the rebel movement to sit at the negotiating 
table for a third time to reach a peace forula accepted by all 
elbashir told the crowd in omdurman khartoums twin city across 
the nile river 
the revolution is determined to make this year a year of peace 
in sudan and to make the last decade in the century an era of 
reform and development by uniting the national efforts 
rebel leader john garang said on clandestine rebel radio that 
his forces would continue to resist sudans dictatorial 
oppressive and repressive military government 
representatives of elbeshir who led a coup that overthrew 
prime minister sadek elmahdis civilian government on june 30 
have held two rounds of talks with the rebel sudan peoples 
liberation army 
the latter one was in nairobi in november mediated by former 
us president jimmy carter rebel leaders and carter said the 
november talks collapsed because of conflicting points of view 
between the two sides and that no date was mentioned for resuming 
them 
but spokesmen for the government have said that while some 
issues were disputed positions acceptable to both sides were found 
for others the government officials said the two sides agreed to 
meet again 
on a recent tour of southern africa officials of the rebel 
movement urged the government to repeal islamic law lift the state 
of emergency announce a ceasefire and abrogate military pacts 
with other countries 
garang in his radio broadcast that was monitored in kenya also 
accused elbashir of insincerity in peace talks 
our experience in the talks confirmed that the junta does 
not have any program for peace and at the same time has rejected 
our proposals to form a broadbased government said garang 
garang a former army colonel who formed the rebel sudan 
peoples liberation army in 1983 said his forces would continue 
resisting the junta since it is imposing itself and its dictatorial 
policy on our masses 
in his comments marking the 34th anniversary of sudans 
independence as well as the new year garang called on all 
opposition movements in sudan to unite in their struggle against 
this dictatorial oppressive and repressive regime 
the rebels have been fighting sudans moslemdominated 
government for greater autonomy and economic reforms for the 
countrys predominantly christian and african south 
the rebels said no date was mentioned for resuming the 
negotiations however government representatives said the talks 
ended with both sides agreeing to meet again 
