<TEXT>
after two years of soaring homicide 
statistics district of columbia police hope a combination of more 
officers and increased community involvement will curb the carnage 
in the nations capital 
were sort of optimistic and we think we have the key 
ingredients to turn this thing around said police spokesman lt 
reginald smith were beginning to realize more community 
support and we need a lot of that if we are going to avoid setting 
another murder record 
washington became known as the murder capital of america after 
two consecutive years of recordsetting homicides the city of 
650000 ended 1989 with an unofficial total of 438 killings a 
record that topped the previous high of 369 recorded in 1988 
police have blamed drugs particularly crack cocaine for more 
than 60 percent of these deaths 
we still see drugs as a big problem but people in the 
community are beginning to be fed up and are patrolling their 
neighborhoods serving as the eyes and ears we need smith said 
in a recent interview we cant be everywhere and we need these 
people to stand up 
police chief isaac fulwood upon taking office last august 
immediately called upon citizens to get involved by alerting police 
to the whereabouts of murder suspects or when they witness a crime 
while smith said community patrols are beginning to work police 
are also pinning their hopes on the 1000 extra officers congress 
and the city have agreed to provide 
when we get those officers out on the street no doubt they 
will have an impact smith said we will increase our presence 
in neighborhoods where we are already active and improve coverage 
elsewhere 
the city has an authorized strength of 4055 officers but the 
new hires will increase the police force to almost 5100 officers 
smith said about 250 new hires are enrolled in the departments 
sixmonth training program while a nationwide recruiting drive is 
being conducted to find the rest 
the first new officers should hit the streets by early spring 
smith said 
the federal government is footing the bill for 700 new officers 
and will pay their salaries and benefits for the next five years 
while the city has included money in its budget to hire 300 extra 
police 
the city also will attempt to rehire retired officers to handle 
desk work in an effort to get younger officers out into the 
community 
but police have already learned that more arrests wont solve 
the crime problem more than 46000 people have been arrested in an 
antidrug sweep that began in 1987 but drug sales continue the 
same has been true for killings 
were not going to be naive and say this thing is going to go 
away overnight smith said it will take time to turn this 
around and really some sort of fundamental change in attitude 
where there is a respect for life 
