west virginia will continue to walk picket lines until union 
members decide whether to approve a new tentative contract 
agreement a union official said monday 
the united mine workers and the pittston co parent of pittston 
coal group announced the tentative agreement monday after 
protracted bargaining sessions in washington dc over the 
holidays 
the violenceplagued 9monthold strike idled 1700 coal miners 
in virginia west virginia and kentucky at one point it sparked 
sympathy walkouts by 46000 miners in nearly a dozen states 
terms of the settlement were not disclosed with both sides 
saying they wanted the miners to hear details from their leaders 
umw president richard trumka said specifics should go to the rank 
and file within eight to 10 days 
i noticed they used the term tentative when they announced 
the agreement the miners will stay on the picket line until 
notified otherwise said howard green a umw international board 
member from charlestonbased district 17 
picket lines at pittstons logan county mines were not manned on 
new years day 
as far as tuesday picketing goes were taking it as just 
another day said roger nelson umw member from boone county and 
coordinator of camp solidarity ii in logan county 
miners drifted in and out of the camp monday while word of the 
tentative settlement circulated the camp was set up in a 
vacant department store to give miners their families and 
supporters a place to congregate sleep and eat over the holidays 
larry ward president of umw district 6 covering ohio and west 
virginias northern panhandle welcomed the tentative settlement 
and said it was worth the sacrifice 
its just a matter of whether you fight for the people who 
gave us this union or just throw them away like the companies do 
ward said 
in virginia striking miners said they hoped they will be back 
on the job soon 
well be receptive to it probably said jack bartee a 
26year veteran of the virginia mines and one of a handful of 
striking miners at the socalled camp solidarity in russell county 
minutes after learning of the tentative agreement southwestern 
virginia miner freddie wallace got a telephone call from labor 
secretary elizabeth dole whom he met in october during her visit 
to the region 
she told me she hoped this contract would mean a happy new 
year and i told her it would said wallace 47 a 
thirdgeneration coal miner 
in kentucky striking miners were happy with the tentative 
agreement announcement said bobby roy justice of district 30 
everybodys just tickled that theres a contract 
logan county pittston miner everett street who served on the 
picket lines for eight months before the union moved him to camp 
solidarity ii said the strike couldnt be over soon enough 
im not real happy if youve been out of work nine months 
you cant be real happy street said he and others said theyre 
waiting to hear the terms of the agreement before making a judgment 
street nelson and local 1971 president dave collins predicted 
some friction between other company employees and the strikers if 
they return to work 
anytime you stand in front of a mack truck coming down on you 
nudging you it cant be peachy when you get back street said 
street was referring to attempts by pittston coal trucks to 
cross picket lines to reach the companys elkay mining co at slab 
fork 
collins said miners must remember that an agreement doesnt 
necessarily translate into employment 
we cant tell the company what mines have to stay open he 
said 
