twenty us diplomats that president 
daniel ortega ordered expelled in retaliation for the search of its 
ambassadors residence in panama by american forces left nicaragua 
monday night 
the diplomats refused to speak with reporters before they and 
their families boarded a commercial flight to miami 
nicaraguas sandinista government gave the americans 72 hours to 
leave the country and ordered the us embassy support staff in 
managua slashed from 320 employees to 100 on friday after us 
troops raided ambassador antenor ferreys home in panama city 
us officials said the troops were searching for weapons and 
courteously withdrew about four hours after they arrived when 
they learned it was a diplomatic residence a us army colonel in 
charge of the operation later apologized and returned rifles that 
had been confiscated ferrey said 
president bush in texas on vacation also apologized for the 
incident but expressed wonder at the amount of arms found inside 
the residence 
the us state department called nicaraguas retaliation an 
irresponsible overreaction 
ortega described it as a very moderate response 
the departure leaves the embassy with 15 diplomats the minimum 
that a host government can restrict an embassy under international 
agreement and nine marine guards 
the incidents raised tension between the united states and 
nicaragua less than two months before the scheduled feb 25 general 
elections 
nicaragua views the panama invasion as proof of its assertion 
